# 7. 知りたいこと

Akito: Man, I wasn't expecting to hear that.
Toya: Yes, I'm also a bit surprised.
Toya: “Mr. Lloyd?”
Toya: “In your opinion, what kind of student was my dad?”
Lloyd: “What kind of student was he? Well...”
Lloyd: “Like I said a second ago, he was basically a monk.”
Lloyd: “Oh, but also very stubborn.”
An: Uhh... I didn't catch that last part.
Kohane: Hehe. He was apparently very stubborn.
An: “Yes, I can kind of see that!”
Akito: Based on what you've told us about him, Toya, he's as hard-headed as they get.
Lloyd: “Haha. To be fair, I'm not one to talk.”
Lloyd: “When it comes to music, there are certain things in which I'm not willing to compromise.”
Lloyd: “But...”
Lloyd: “Harumichi was a musician I respected very much. I feel like I learned something every time we played together.”
Toya: “Every time you played together...?”
Lloyd: “Yes, we swapped genres from time to time, and even played completely random music.”
Lloyd: “Each time I stepped out of my area of expertise, I was given a chance to objectively assess my playing abilities.”
Lloyd: “Not only that, I learned new ways of expressing myself through my music.”
Toya: “I see... That does sound like a good way to learn.”
Toya: (But it's also easier said than done.)
Toya: (When I first started singing street music, my habits from playing classical music hindered me quite a lot.)
Toya: (Dad and Mr. Lloyd probably had no issue dipping their feet in other genres because they were both great musicians already.)
Lloyd: “So, Toya, since you and your friends are here, would you all like to give it a try?”
Toya: Huh...?
Kohane: Give what a try...?
Lloyd: “Ah, perfect. I see some students doing a session in the courtyard.”
Lloyd: “Hey!”
Student Ａ: “Hm? Is Professor Lloyd telling us to come over?”
Student Ｂ: “Do you think that group's here to visit the school?”
Lloyd: “Were you all just having a session?”
Student Ａ: “Yes, we're done with our morning classes, so we decided to do one for fun.”
Toya: (A violin, a cello and a saxophone... As far as sessions go, that seems like a standard combination of instruments, but...)
An: Wow, I've never seen some of these instruments before...
Kohane: Yeah... Oh, what do you think that silver pan is called?
Toya: I believe it's a steelpan. I remember seeing it in a book once.
Toya: They're apparently made out of steel drums, and you can produce different sounds depending on where you strike it.
An: Really...?!
Akito: I'm having trouble imagining how we're gonna have a session using all these instruments...
Toya: Me too...
Toya: (But Mr. Lloyd just asked if we'd like to give this a try.)
Toya: (Which means...)
Lloyd: “Would you all mind letting these kids play with you? They'll be singing.”
An: What...?!
Student Ｂ: “We don't mind.”
Student Ｃ: “That's perfect, since there aren't any vocalists around today.”
An: Umm... Singing with them does sound fun...
Akito: But completely on the fly...? Is that gonna be possible for us?
Toya: (Yes, we aren't just dealing with street music here. We have a blend of genres...)
Toya: (I honestly can't imagine what our performance is going to sound like...)
Lloyd: “Harumichi used to participate in these sorts of sessions back in the day.”
Toya: ...! “Is that true?”
Lloyd: “Yes. When I first met him, he always had this serious and curmudgeonly expression on his face.”
Lloyd: “But after he played in one of these sessions, I saw him smile for the first time. He seemed to genuinely enjoy himself.”
Toya: “Dad? Having fun...?”
Lloyd: “Yes, it was quite a surprise.”
Toya: (To think these sessions could hold that kind of power...)
Toya: (Then...)
Toya: I'd like to give it a try.
Akito: Toya...
Toya: If there's anything our trip to the United States has taught me so far, it's that I still know very little.
Toya: I'm not just talking about the things I missed out on when I was little.
Toya: I dreamed of playing like my dad... But it's clear now that I knew nothing about the truth behind his music.
Toya: Which is why I want to know more. I want to participate in this session and try to experience what he did...
Toya: I want to know how his music evolved.
Akito: Alright, why not?
Akito: We came all this way to America, so we should be making the most of every opportunity we get.
An: Right! And this session is sure to help us!
Kohane: Let's give it a try, Aoyagi.
Toya: Thank you all very much.
